The two men signed a pact a year ago to end a civil war that has killed hundreds of thousands of people, displaced a third of the population and wrecked the economy. Machar made a rare visit to Juba this week to meet Kiir. "The parties discussed minor issues and the principals agreed to establish transitional government by November 12," Michael Makuei Lueth, the Information Minister, told reporters. The roll-out of last year's accord, which called for a unity government, has been delayed because the government says it does not have enough money to fund disarmament and the integration of all the armed factions. --Reuters--